2026-03-23 | Longest Cycle in Directed Graph

	Question
Return the length of the longest cycle in the graph.

	Approach
1.	Use a **visited array** to track visited nodes.
2.	Also track:
		time (step count when visiting nodes)
3.	For each node:
		if not visited:
			start traversal
4.	Maintain a map:
		node → time visited in current path
5.	If during traversal we reach a node already in current path:
		cycle detected  
		cycle length = currentTime - storedTime
6.	Update maximum cycle length.
7.	Mark nodes as globally visited.

	Time Complexity
	O(V)

	Space Complexity
	O(V)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    int longestCycle(vector<vector<int>>& edges) {

        int n = edges.size();
        vector<int> vis(n, 0);
        int ans = -1;

        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){

            if(vis[i]) continue;

            unordered_map<int,int> mp;
            int node = i;
            int step = 0;

            while(node != -1 && !vis[node]){

                vis[node] = 1;
                mp[node] = step++;

                int next = edges[node][1]; // u -> v

                if(next != -1 && mp.count(next)){
                    ans = max(ans, step - mp[next]);
                    break;
                }

                node = next;
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

	Key Insight
Since each node has **at most one outgoing edge**,  
we don’t need full DFS branching.

Instead:
- follow the path linearly  
- detect cycle using **visit time tracking**  

This gives an optimal **O(V)** solution.
